post_text:
We encourage all families to fill out a Free/Reduced Meal Application even though Winfield school district families are currently receiving free meals through the schools. The current “free for all” meals will end sometime soon and we want to be prepared. Also, funding for various school related programs is linked to these applications.

The official student count day is September 21st. Additional state funding allocations are given to distribute based on the number of students who qualify for free/reduced meals and the information is based on the outcomes of submitted applications by that date.

When the funding for the free meal program runs out, students will return to full pay for meals unless we have a current approved application on file.

Even if you do not think your family would qualify, we appreciate you taking the time to file. Applications are available at each school building and at the District Office located at 1407 Wheat Road.

I was recently the guest of @pdxradioproject on Early Link Podcast. You can listen to it on the link above or on iTunes! Thanks for having me, Rafael and Early Link!

“Rosproy shares her experience with engaging families in student learning and highlights the necessity of a partnership between teachers and caregivers for student success. She also talks about the importance of keeping students connected to one another during distance learning. As Tabatha looks towards the next year, she discusses her plans to use her new platform to advocate for early learning educators across the country.”

#ntoy20

Viking Boosters - Winfield, KS
June 14 at 8:38 PM ·

Edit: All current shifts have been filled as of June 15th! Thanks to those who replied!

The Viking Booster Club operates the concession stand at Broadway Sports complex during the summer. We have shifts available for individuals who are interested in working to earn funds for USD 465 school activities. This opportunity is for class of 2021, 2022, 2023 & 2024 WHS High School Students. Shifts are typically weekday evenings: two games per night; typically shifts are 5:30 pm to 9 pm (must stay until fields finish). If you are interested, please private message or call for more information.

post_text: Update for our Cumbernauld Little Vikes program.
shared_text:
Winfield Early Learning Center
June 15 at 7:27 AM ·

Due to the current situation regarding COVID-19 and anticipated health precautions at Cumbernauld Village, the district preschool classroom which resides within the Cumbernauld Village facility will be located within the Winfield Early Learning Center for the 2020-2021 school year.

Cumbernauld Village and USD 465 are hopeful to resume this partnership for the 2021-2022 school year. Of course, this is contingent on health and safety guidelines at that time.

Though the classroom will be temporarily housed at the Winfield Early Learning Center, USD 465 plans to keep strong ties to Cumbernauld Village, and grandparent volunteers. We will do everything in our power to keep the residents and our students connected during this unprecedented time while maintaining vigilance in keeping everyone safe and healthy.

shared_text:
Winfield High School
May 11 at 10:35 AM ·

Based on an order by Governor Kelly, the Winfield High School Senior Parade on May 17th has been cancelled. The staff is highly disappointed but respect the decisions of our State and Local Leaders. We will honor the decisions made to attempt to keep us safe, healthy, and Viking Strong.

Winfield High School encourages the public to go outside and honk their horn at 2:00pm on May 17th to honor what would have been an important day in these students' lives. We will also be releasing a special video on Sunday to commemorate these seniors.

We are continuing to look forward to Graduation on July 25th!

post_text:
Meet Aaron and Adam! They are part of the USD 465 Tech Department Team. They are the people who test, build, install, repair, and maintain the hardware and software associated with our computer systems throughout the district. They are the people that have been working tirelessly to keep Continuous Learning running smoothly. We cannot express enough how important these two are to USD 465! THANK YOU, AARON AND ADAM!

Adam has exciting news to share: he is getting married in August! 😊

Aaron is sad that garage sale season has not been able to start yet. 😔

post_text: USD 465 is offering drive in Wi-Fi access at two locations beginning April 23rd. We understand that access to consistent Wi-Fi for our students can sometimes be a challenge. Students can find the two Wi-Fi locations in front of Country View Elementary School and just south of Irving Elementary at the Transportation Center. Look for these signs and park near them for the best Wi-Fi coverage. Student access is priority. Please follow the directions on the posted signs, stay in your vehicles, and maintain proper social distancing.

post_text: AWESOME job Whittier!!
shared_text:
Marcia Jones McIntire‎Whittier Elementary PTO
April 17 at 8:45 PM ·

Whittier was notified today we were selected as a Kansas State School of Character and given the Enhanced Spotlight Recognition Award for our work in literacy (One School, One Book Project) and our work in Social, Emotional and Character Development (Student Council, Earth Club, Movers and Shakers, Meals on Wheels, Humane Society, Triple S, Tech Team, Library Aides and more!). There will be a virtual ceremony on May 12th-we will share the information as it becomes available so you can attend! We are very humbled and honored by such an award that comes from the Kansas State Board of Education, character.org and Smoky Hill Education Service Center! So proud of our Whittier community!!! #VikingStrong #WhittierStrong

Wowza!! Will ya look at that. WHS is proud to announce 7 WHS seniors have been named as 2020 Kansas State Scholars. This is an amazing accomplishment💙 Out of 6,262 seniors across the state just 2,641 have been named as state scholars. The average GPA for those selected was 3.91 and the average ACT was 30! If you have a way to virtually congratulate these WHS seniors please do!!! Congrats!

post_text: In the last few weeks the look of food service in our schools has drastically changed. Instead of cafeterias full of students, meals are being prepared and packaged and delivered to schools for pickup and loaded onto buses for delivery. That is a huge change in a short time for food service employees. If you have been around the kitchen at WMS/WHS you have probably seen this face. This lady wears a smile every day and has a quick wit that doesn’t stop. She has gone above and beyond what has been expected of her and I know the children in our community appreciate the job she does. THANK YOU, CASEY!

post_text:
In the last few weeks the look of school classes has changed dramatically from what we are used to seeing. Students are now learning from home and teachers and staff have done a tremendous job of being flexible and trying new techniques. Many of the changes are behind the scenes and we would like to recognize some of our employees that are invaluable to this new way of learning and to say thank you.

Many of you know Bernie as the custodian at WMS and WHS. What you may not know is that Bernie has been helping every day to get lunches and breakfasts prepared and packed for the children in our community. THANK YOU, BERNIE!

post_text: Winfield High School student belongings pick up schedule.
shared_text:
Winfield High School
March 24 at 8:30 AM ·

We will be gathering all students' belongings from lockers, classrooms, and gym lockers. We will start returning these items Wednesday, March 25th.

Please approach the south entrance to the aux gym from the east. We will pass out locker items from the south aux doors. Let us know if you have items from gym lockers, band instruments, or medication at that time.

To help follow the state guidelines we will work off of this schedule.
Wednesday, 3/25: 8:00-9:30 Seniors
9:30-11:00 Juniors
12:00-1:30 Soph.
1:30-3:00 Freshman
Thursday will be anyone that could not make it Wednesday.

If you have students in different grades, you may pick up all their stuff at one time. If students have been sharing a locker with another student it will be up to them to get those items back.

Also, please return school textbooks, library books, and school-owned instruments at this time.

post_text: A whole lot of fun at Whittier Elementary!
shared_text:
Marcia Jones McIntire‎Whittier Elementary PTO
March 8 at 5:22 PM ·

Friday afternoon was our Third Annual Pancake Flipping Contest for staff. It was, as usual, tons of fun and loud as the kiddos loved cheering on the staff who flipped pancakes up and down the gym floor. Two teams, coached by a stack of pancakes and a bottle of maple syrup and an announcer decked out like a box of butter began the event. The two teams were all decked out with their "names", aprons and more! Mad flipping prevailed and the winners were honored with a gold plated syrup bottle and spatula while the runner up team received gold plated silverware. Lots of fun!! Shout out to Stephanie Shutt-Anderson at McDonald's for the pancakes and Kimberly McPherson Randall for the costumes!!

shared_text:
Cumbernauld Little Vikes - USD 465 Intergenerational Preschool added 17 new photos to the album: Christmas Kindness, Week 1.
December 6, 2019 at 11:54 AM ·

Rather than watching kids to make sure they aren’t being naughty, our Elf On the Shelf is a kindness elf who brings us new ideas each day to spread kindness in the world! We think that what you focus on, you get more of! And the world always needs more kindness. ❤️

This week we have hung candy canes on cars, made cards to mail loved ones we don’t see very often, made bird seed ornaments to feed the birds, made ornaments for our principal, and made decorations for Cumbernauld to spread Christmas cheer!

post_text: AWESOME job, Vikings!
shared_text:
Marcia Jones McIntire‎Whittier Elementary PTO
November 19, 2019 at 9:09 PM ·

Today was our Fall Leadership Assembly and what a wonderful morning we had at Whittier!! The assembly began with a terrific message from our guest speaker, City Manager Taggart Wall! We were so pleased with his speech and very proud of this USD 465 2007 WHS Graduate! He had the entire group in a pledge about how strong, how smart and how kind they are and can be! Sixteen students were honored by staff for their demonstration of character traits that help create our future leaders!! From Kindergarten through Fifth Grade, students were surprised when their names were called (it was a secret!) and their families were present beaming with pride. After the assembly, students hung their pictures on our Leadership Bulletin Board in the Leadership Hallway. Another great day at Camp Whittier and it all happened during American Education Week!! Thank you staff and families for your continued support of our future leaders! #campwhittierisfullofleaders

“Encourage, lift and strengthen one another. For the positive energy spread to one will be felt by us all. For we are connected, one and all.”
— Deborah Day
shared_text:
Lowell Elementary School is with Loron Hays.
November 14, 2019 at 1:24 PM ·

Today in Mrs.Shields 1st grade class, students each wrote their name on a piece of paper. Then they passed each paper around and everyone got a chance to write something nice about that person on their paper. At the end, the papers eventually made their way back to the original owner, and they got to read all the nice comments from each of their classmates. Everyone had huge smiles on their faces as they filled each others buckets and their own buckets were filled with positive words and feelings. ❤️

shared_text:
Cumbernauld Little Vikes - USD 465 Intergenerational Preschool
November 5, 2019 at 10:50 PM ·

Children learn best when they can access their executive skills in their prefrontal lobe. In times of distress, when BIG feelings get ahold of us, we can't access those skills, because we are operating from a different part of our brains.

We've been working on deep belly breathing and being a S.T.A.R. (Smile, take a deep breath, and relax) to help us move to a higher center in our brains, so we can think and solve problems! In this photo, we are watching our Feeling Buddies move up and down as we take slow, deep breaths.

Learning to manage feelings must be as intentional as learning to read.

#preschool #mrstabathasclass #cumbernauldlittlevikes #iheartcd
